de.uni.bamberg.wiai.minf.forflow.datagenerator.view
Class DataGeneratorView

java.lang.Object
  org.jdesktop.application.AbstractBean
      org.jdesktop.application.View
          org.jdesktop.application.FrameView
              de.uni.bamberg.wiai.minf.forflow.datagenerator.view.DataGeneratorView
All Implemented Interfaces:
ObserverDistribution, ObserverGenerator, ObserverUnit, ObserverUnitCustom, ObserverArtefact
public class DataGeneratorView
extends org.jdesktop.application.FrameView
implements ObserverArtefact, ObserverUnit, ObserverUnitCustom, ObserverGenerator, ObserverDistribution

DataGeneratorView class is the main view. Here are the components of the UI created and initialized. Most of the actions are not directly handled her, but passed on.

To get updated with the latest news and informations about the model layer, it implements some Observer interfaces. With this, the UI is gonna be updated whenever a change in the subject occurs. The subject is in terms of the observer pattern the observable.

http://java.sun.com/docs/books/tutorial/uiswing/

deleteArtefact

@Action
public void deleteArtefact()
this method is comparable with deleteFacet(), but it deletes a whole artefact out of the model instead of a facet. Has this method been executed, there is now way to restore it.

The option to delete an artefact is only possible, if a tree component has the current focus. Otherwise it's ignored. With this approach we make sure, that one has first to select the node in the tree to kick and then explicitly calling the delete function.

If the fix root element has been selected to delete, it is thrown an error message to point out the mistake.

loadProject

@Action
public void loadProject()
if a session has been serialized with method saveProject(), it is possible to deserialize it and work further.

The advantage of this is clear: one doesn't have to get to the latest point in defining test data manually, but automatically. The whole process doesn't have to be redone and small changes in the definition parameters can be adjusted.

fillTypeEditorIncrement

@Action
public void fillTypeEditorIncrement()
used by: FillType.Editor

sometimes it is useful to increment one value rather than typing in a whole bunch of different ones.
When to use?
This is especially true, when file names are generated. In the file system are usually files containing the same file name but have different version numbers, as an example. This is simulated with the increment option.

Example
Here is a quick example on how the values in the editor are used. Suppose you've typed in something like this:
Presentation_
Order
Contract with Certkiller.com

Furthermore, we assume the increment function has been enabled. The generated values for the 1st increment and the last will be:
Presentation_0
Order0
Contract with Certkiller.com 0
...
Presentation_n
Ordern
Contract with Certkiller.com n

There is still one thing to mention. Only those values will be incremented which are actually taken for generation. When available?
The option is only available when the editor is used as the fill behaviour. If you save the typed in values as an value file and then link it with external file the option will not be available anymore.

fillTypeIntervalAccept

@Action
public void fillTypeIntervalAccept()
used by: fillType.Interval
Defining an interval is useful, when values of a given attribute have known lower & upper bounds.

Example:

The thread length of screws has such a lower and upper bound. The minimum length is '1' and the maximum is '14' cm. That leads to the following situation:
  • 1, 2, ..., 14
As a result of the above restricts, the interval could be described as:
  1. ]0, 15[
  2. [1, 15[
  3. ]0, 14]
  4. [1, 14]
The typed in interval will be parsed and validated. In case the interval passes the validation test it is set into the filling type of the currently selected row. But if the interval fails the validation the typed in text is gonna be erased by the system and the cursor is set into the corresponding text field.

updateProbabilityDistribution

public void updateProbabilityDistribution(boolean add,
                                          ProbabilityDistribution distribution)
Description copied from interface: ObserverDistribution
The method makes sure the observer gets the latest updates about probability distributions (subject). The update doesn't notify about changes in the data structure, but notifies about removing or adding a probability distribution to a list of available distributions. The list is usually somewhere in the UI.

Register
When a notification is send out to the observer, the flag is set to true, that means a new subject has been created. The creating is done in controller layer but the view layer gets a notification about that.

Un-register
Un-registering means the subject, that is a probability distribution, is gonna be eliminated from the model layer. Removing can only do the controller layer, but to make sure the view gets the latest update the subject itself sends and notification about the status.

Specified by:
updateProbabilityDistribution in interface ObserverDistribution
Parameters:
add - flag, indicates the operation to do. That could be to add a probability distribution to or removing one from the list.
distribution - this is the subject which has send the notification.
